MyPers2

Data screening

  • Country: 1776914 observations (user id + country of provenance)
  • Dem: 4282857 observations of 15 variables (including sex, date of birth, age, relationship status, etc.)
    • Besides sex, all variables present a huge number of missing data
    • 34.6% of the observations are coded as gender 0, 63.5% as 1 (1.88% is missing)
    • The variable age is strongly right skewed with a mean of 26 years, but 63% of the information is missing
  • Schwartz: 12073 observations recording values from Schwartz Values Survey, which measures goals, aspirations and wishes that drive behaviour.
    • Values refer to SVS 57 (version of the test introdueced in the 1990s, more information can be found at https://github.com/artearthtech/cultural-values/issues/1)
    • Includes date of the test, test completed or not (0/1), and answers to the 57 questions
  • LDA (Latent Dirichlet allocation): 111431 observations of 600 variables
    • Each row represents a user, each column quantifies how much the user has in common with the 600 topics
    • Topics are stored in the variable lda_topic_names, that contains 600 rows and 5 columns (the 5 Facebook pages that mostly relate to the topic)
    • Research question: Do these topics identify coherent groups of fb pages that are internally homogenous, and are related to each other in a meaningful way? Does variation in topic usage correspond with certain characteristics? Do the topics match existing measures (e.g. sex, religion) where they should match?
  • SVD: number of variables from the LDA data has been reduced to 100 topics
  • Religion: 331671 observations containing political (e.g. conservative/liberal/moderate) and religious view

SVS 57

The SVS survey presents two lists of value items. The first contains 30 items that "describe potentially desirable end-states in noun form; the second contains 27 items that describe potentially desirable ways of acting in adjective form".

Respondents rate the importance of each value item ”as a guiding principle in MY life" on a 9-point scale labeled 7 (of supreme importance), 6 (very important), ..., 0 (not important), -1 (opposed to my values).

SVS57 scores have been computed for each individual, following the SVS guidlines that link each question to a personal characteristic as follows:

Power = 3, 12, 27

Achievement = 34, 43, 55, 39

Hedonism = 4, 50, 57

Stimulation = 9, 25, 37

Selfdirection = 5, 16, 31, 41, 53

Universalism = 1, 17, 24, 26, 29, 30, 35, 38

Benevolence = 33, 45, 49, 52, 54

Tradition = 36, 44, 51, 32

Conformity = 11, 20, 40, 47

Security = 13, 15, 56, 8, 22

However, questions 6, 23 and 46 do not have a particular indication.

These values are considered as in the Schwartz Circumplex Model (Schawrtz, 2012), which defines 10 value domains as in the following picture:

The values are organized along two bipolar dimensions to “summarize the oppositions between competing values”.

As the figure above shows, “one dimension contrasts ‘openness to change’ and ‘conservation’ values. This dimension captures the conflict between values that emphasize independence of thought, action, and feelings and readiness for change (self-direction, stimulation) and values that emphasize order, selfrestriction, preservation of the past, and resistance to change (security, conformity, tradition).

The second dimension contrasts ‘self-enhancement’ and ‘self-transcendence’ values. This dimension captures the conflict between values that emphasize concern for the welfare and interests of others (universalism, benevolence) and values that emphasize pursuit of one’s own interests and relative success and dominance over others (power, achievement).

Hedonism shares elements of both openness to change and self-enhancement.”

The first factor has only positive values.

Power (3, 12, 27) is catched by very high positive loadings in the second factor. Same for Achievement (34, 43, 55, 39), with positive but lower loadings.

Universalism (1, 17, 24, 26, 29, 30, 35, 38) is catched by negative loadings in the second factor.

Hedonism (4, 50, 57) loads on both the second (positively) and third (negatevely) factors, coherently for each item. Same for Stimulation (9, 50, 57).

Security (13, 15, 56, 8, 22) has positive loadings for both the second and third factor.

Benevolence (33, 45, 49, 52, 54) has positive loadings for the third factor and, for some items, negative ones on the second factor.

Tradition (36, 44, 51, 32) and Conformity (11, 20, 40, 47) are catched by positive loadings in the third factor. Selfdirection (5, 16, 31, 41, 53) loads negatively on the third factor.

Following the Shwartz model:

  • The third factor well represents Conservation (positive loadings on Conformity + Tradition + Security) and Openess (negative loadings on Stimulation + Selfdirection).

  • The second factor well represents Self enhancement (positive loadings on Achivement + Power + Hedonism) and Self transcendence (negative loadings on Benevolence + Universalism).

Looking at the theoretical model scheme, this is exactly what was expected. The model is able to catch these relations from the survey data in a meaningful way.

Train/test split

  • Train set has 90% of the total people from US (1305 persons)

  • Test set has the remaining 10% from US + all people from other countries with at least 20 units (countries in the European Union have been joined together so to reach a sufficient amount of units). Test set includes 380 persons:

  • 146 people from US
  • 59 people from Canada
  • 55 people from the Philippines
  • 35 people from the Europen Union (Czech Republic, Portugal, Italy, Netherlands, Norway, Serbia, Sweden, Spain, Finland, France, Germany, Denmark)
  • 29 people from India
  • 28 people from UK

  • 28 people from Australia

Using the R package xgboost, the training data have been used to train the algorithm in predicting factors from the corresponding 10 SVS57 values.

Two models have been built:

  • Model 1: using Factor 2
  • Model 2: using Factor 3

Model 1

Parameters optimisation has been investigated:

watchlist_grid2 <- list(train=xgb.DMatrix(data = as.matrix(joined_10fold_train[,V2:V601]),
                                    label = as.matrix(joined_10fold_train[, Factor2])),
                  test=xgb.DMatrix(data = as.matrix(joined_10fold_test[, V2:V601]),
                                   label = as.matrix(joined_10fold_test[, Factor2])))

# hyper-parameter search
searchGrid = expand.grid(
nrounds = 50,
eta = c(0.01, 0.001, 0.0001),
max_depth = c(2, 4, 6, 8, 10),
subsample=c(0.4, 0.5, 0.6, 0.7),
lambda=c(0.01, 0.1, 0.8),
alpha=c(0.001,0.01,0.1)
)

rmseHyperparameters <- apply(searchGrid, 1, function(parameterList){

  #Extract Parameters to test
  currentmax_depth <- parameterList[["max_depth"]]
  currentsubsample <- parameterList[["subsample"]]
  currentlambda <- parameterList[["lambda"]]
  currentEta <- parameterList[["eta"]]
  currentalpha <- parameterList[["alpha"]]

  xgb_2 <- xgb.train(data =  watchlist_grid2$train,
                       metrics = "rmse", "eval_metric" = "rmse",
                     "objective" = "reg:linear", "max.depth" = currentmax_depth, "eta" = currentEta,
                     "subsample" = currentsubsample, "lambda" = currentlambda, "alpha" = currentalpha, nrounds=50)

pred_xg_2 <- predict(xgb_2, newdata = as.matrix(joined_10fold_test[, V2:V601]))

y_test_2 <- as.numeric(joined_10fold_test[, Factor2])

corr=cor(pred_xg_2, y_test_2)^2

mse_xgboost_model1 <- mean((joined_10fold_test[,Factor2] - pred_xg_2)^2)
  output <- return(c(corr, mse_xgboost_model1, currentsubsample, currentlambda, currentmax_depth, currentEta, currentalpha))

})

output <- as.data.frame(t(rmseHyperparameters))
varnames <- c("corr", "mse", "subsample", "lambda", "max_depth", "eta", "alpha")
names(output) <- varnames

head(output[order(output$corr, decreasing = TRUE),],5)

Highest correlation is achieved with 0.6 subsample, 0.01 lambda, 10 maxdepth, eta=0.01, alpha=0.1.

Running this model on the actual test set (the one in watchlist, previously specified as 10% of total US + all other countries):

Model 2

Model used in the prediction of factor 3 from LDA scores.

Parameters optimisation has been investigated:

watchlist_grid2 <- list(train=xgb.DMatrix(data = as.matrix(joined_10fold_train[,V2:V601]),
                                    label = as.matrix(joined_10fold_train[, Factor3])),
                  test=xgb.DMatrix(data = as.matrix(joined_10fold_test[, V2:V601]),
                                   label = as.matrix(joined_10fold_test[, Factor3])))

# hyper-parameter search
searchGrid = expand.grid(
nrounds = 30,
eta = c(0.01, 0.001, 0.0001),
max_depth = c(2, 4, 6, 8, 10),
subsample=c(0.4, 0.5, 0.6, 0.7),
lambda=c(0.01, 0.1, 0.8),
alpha=c(0.001,0.01,0.1)
)

rmseHyperparameters <- apply(searchGrid, 1, function(parameterList){

  #Extract Parameters to test
  currentmax_depth <- parameterList[["max_depth"]]
  currentsubsample <- parameterList[["subsample"]]
  currentlambda <- parameterList[["lambda"]]
  currentEta <- parameterList[["eta"]]
  currentalpha <- parameterList[["alpha"]]

  xgb_2 <- xgb.train(data =  watchlist_grid2$train,
                       metrics = "rmse", "eval_metric" = "rmse",
                     "objective" = "reg:linear", "max.depth" = currentmax_depth, "eta" = currentEta,
                     "subsample" = currentsubsample, "lambda" = currentlambda, "alpha" = currentalpha, nrounds=30)

pred_xg_2 <- predict(xgb_2, newdata = as.matrix(joined_10fold_test[, V2:V601]))

y_test_2 <- as.numeric(joined_10fold_test[, Factor3])

corr=cor(pred_xg_2, y_test_2)^2

mse_xgboost_model1 <- mean((joined_10fold_test[,Factor3] - pred_xg_2)^2)
  output <- return(c(corr, mse_xgboost_model1, currentsubsample, currentlambda, currentmax_depth, currentEta, currentalpha))

})

output <- as.data.frame(t(rmseHyperparameters))
varnames <- c("corr", "mse", "subsample", "lambda", "max_depth", "eta", "alpha")
names(output) <- varnames

head(output[order(output$corr, decreasing = TRUE),],5)
